During ex-situ BM, substrates are supplied in the gaseous form, and they exchange with the liquid phase, where, CO2 dissolves in the liquid phase according to Eq. 3. Depending on pH during the process, the CO2 solubility sharply increases around pH = 8.0 where the twofold higher CO2 concentration can be dissolved in the liquid phase compared to pH = 6.0. With increasing pH, the CO2 is represented by ionized forms such bicarbonate (HCO3−) and carbonate (CO32−) where the equilibrium point (pK) for CO2/HCO3− is pH = 6.3 while for HCO3−/CO32− is pH = 10.3 (Goldberg et al. 2002).3CO2+H2O→HCO3-+H+\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
